elief that it was a genuine but unauthenticated work by [[Marc Chagall]]. Forensic tests showed that it was painted with pigments not available at the time it was purported to have been painted. It was submitted to the "Chagall Committee", who ruled that it was a fake and ordered its destruction.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2014/feb/01/chagall-could-be-furnt-fortune-or-fake|title=The man whose 'real Chagall' could now be burnt as a fake|first=Dalya|last=Alberge|date=1 February 2014|accessdate=21 August 2017|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>
